<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-381-128  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 381 128.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  June 26 1989 v35 n1764 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Commercial buying grounded. (Government Closeup) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robertson, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Pentagon ignores its own policy to 'buy commercial' duringcontract negotiations with Honeywell Commercial Flight Systems.andO;The defense contract involved commercial avionic flight controlsystems for the Navy's anti-submarine warfare aircraft.andP;  Lockheed,the supplier of the airplanes, convinced the Navy to use thecommercial flight control systems rather than military avionicsequipment.andP;  Studies have shown that the commercial products equalor exceed military specifications and are a fraction of the cost.andO;Honeywell, under the impression that the contract with the Navywas for commercial products and that the contract was thereforenot subject to federal procurement regulations, submitted aproposal which included 83 objections to the Lockheed subcontract,which made constant reference to federal regulations.andP;  Lawyersadvised Honeywell to withdraw its bid.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Honeywell Inc. Sperry Commercial Flight Systems Group (contracts).andO;Topic:     Government ContractsUnited States. Department of DefenseMilitaryAerospace Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>